  72 TOML_DICT_NAMES = [o.__class__.__name__ for o in TOML_DICT_OBJECTS]

  74 HASH_STRING = " --hash={0}"
  75 
  76 ALPHA_NUMERIC = r"[{0}{1}]".format(string.ascii_letters, string.digits)
  77 PUNCTUATION = r"[\-_\.]"
  78 ALPHANUM_PUNCTUATION = r"[{0}{1}\-_\.]".format(string.ascii_letters, string.digits)
  79 NAME = r"{0}+{1}*{2}".format(ALPHANUM_PUNCTUATION, PUNCTUATION, ALPHA_NUMERIC)
  80 REF = r"[{0}{1}\-\_\./]".format(string.ascii_letters, string.digits)
  81 EXTRAS = r"(?P<extras>\[{0}(?:,{0})*\])".format(NAME)
  82 NAME_WITH_EXTRAS = r"(?P<name>{0}){1}?".format(NAME, EXTRAS)
  83 NAME_RE = re.compile(NAME_WITH_EXTRAS)
  84 SUBDIR_RE = r"(?:[&#]subdirectory=(?P<subdirectory>.*))"
  85 URL_NAME = r"(?:#egg={0})".format(NAME_WITH_EXTRAS)
  86 REF_RE = r"(?:@(?P<ref>{0}+)?)".format(REF)
  87 PATH_RE = r"(?P<pathsep>[:/])(?P<path>[^ @]+){0}?".format(REF_RE)
  88 PASS_RE = r"(?:(?<=:)(?P<password>[^ ]+))"
  89 AUTH_RE = r"(?:(?P<username>[^ ]+)[:@]{0}?@)".format(PASS_RE)
  90 HOST_RE = r"(?:{0}?(?P<host>[^ ]+?\.?{1}+(?P<port>:\d+)?))?".format(
  91     AUTH_RE, ALPHA_NUMERIC
  92 )
  93 URL = r"(?P<scheme>[^ ]+://){0}{1}".format(HOST_RE, PATH_RE)
  94 URL_RE = re.compile(r"{0}(?:{1}?{2}?)?".format(URL, URL_NAME, SUBDIR_RE))
  95 DIRECT_URL_RE = re.compile(r"{0}\s?@\s?{1}".format(NAME_WITH_EXTRAS, URL))

 105 def filter_dict(dict_):
 106     # type: (Dict[AnyStr, Any]) -> Dict[AnyStr, Any]
 107     return {k: v for k, v in dict_.items() if filter_none(k, v)}

 125 def tomlkit_value_to_python(toml_value):
 126     # type: (Union[Array, AoT, TOML_DICT_TYPES, Item]) -> Union[List, Dict]
 127     value_type = type(toml_value).__name__
 128     if (
 129         isinstance(toml_value, TOML_DICT_OBJECTS + (dict,))
 130         or value_type in TOML_DICT_NAMES
 131     ):
 132         return tomlkit_dict_to_python(toml_value)
 133     elif isinstance(toml_value, AoT) or value_type == "AoT":
 134         return [tomlkit_value_to_python(val) for val in toml_value._body]
 135     elif isinstance(toml_value, Array) or value_type == "Array":
 136         return [tomlkit_value_to_python(val) for val in list(toml_value)]
 137     elif isinstance(toml_value, String) or value_type == "String":
 138         return "{0!s}".format(toml_value)
 139     elif isinstance(toml_value, Bool) or value_type == "Bool":
 140         return toml_value.value
 141     elif isinstance(toml_value, Item):
 142         return toml_value.value
 143     return toml_value
 144 
 145 
 146 def tomlkit_dict_to_python(toml_dict):
 147     # type: (TOML_DICT_TYPES) -> Dict
 148     value_type = type(toml_dict).__name__
 149     if toml_dict is None:
 150         raise TypeError("Invalid type NoneType when converting toml dict to python")
 151     converted = None  # type: Optional[Dict]
 152     if isinstance(toml_dict, (InlineTable, Table)) or value_type in (
 153         "InlineTable",
 154         "Table",
 155     ):
 156         converted = toml_dict.value
 157     elif isinstance(toml_dict, (Package, PackageCollection)) or value_type in (
 158         "Package, PackageCollection"
 159     ):
 160         converted = toml_dict._data
 161         if isinstance(converted, Container) or type(converted).__name__ == "Container":
 162             converted = converted.value
 163     elif isinstance(toml_dict, Container) or value_type == "Container":
 164         converted = toml_dict.value
 165     elif isinstance(toml_dict, dict):
 166         converted = toml_dict.copy()
 167     else:
 168         raise TypeError(
 169             "Invalid type for conversion: expected Container, Dict, or Table, "
 170             "got {0!r}".format(toml_dict)
 171         )
 172     if isinstance(converted, dict):
 173         return {k: tomlkit_value_to_python(v) for k, v in converted.items()}
 174     elif isinstance(converted, (TOML_DICT_OBJECTS)) or value_type in TOML_DICT_NAMES:
 175         return tomlkit_dict_to_python(converted)
 176     return converted

 208 def extras_to_string(extras):
 209     # type: (Iterable[S]) -> S
 210     """Turn a list of extras into a string
 211 
 212     :param List[str]] extras: a list of extras to format
 213     :return: A string of extras
 214     :rtype: str
 215     """
 216     if isinstance(extras, six.string_types):
 217         if extras.startswith("["):
 218             return extras
 219         else:
 220             extras = [extras]
 221     if not extras:
 222         return ""
 223     return "[{0}]".format(",".join(sorted(set(extras))))  # type: ignore
 224

 226 def parse_extras(extras_str):
 227     # type: (AnyStr) -> List[AnyStr]
 228     """Turn a string of extras into a parsed extras list
 229 
 230     :param str extras_str: An extras string
 231     :return: A sorted list of extras
 232     :rtype: List[str]
 233     """
 234 
 235     from pkg_resources import Requirement
 236 
 237     extras = Requirement.parse("fakepkg{0}".format(extras_to_string(extras_str))).extras
 238     return sorted(dedup([extra.lower() for extra in extras]))

 241 def specs_to_string(specs):
 242     # type: (List[Union[STRING_TYPE, Specifier]]) -> AnyStr
 243     """Turn a list of specifier tuples into a string
 244 
 245     :param List[Union[Specifier, str]] specs: a list of specifiers to format
 246     :return: A string of specifiers
 247     :rtype: str
 248     """
 249 
 250     if specs:
 251         if isinstance(specs, six.string_types):
 252             return specs
 253         try:
 254             extras = ",".join(["".join(spec) for spec in specs])
 255         except TypeError:
 256             extras = ",".join(["".join(spec._spec) for spec in specs])  # type: ignore
 257         return extras
 258     return ""

 261 def build_vcs_uri(
 262     vcs,  # type: Optional[S]
 263     uri,  # type: S
 264     name=None,  # type: Optional[S]
 265     ref=None,  # type: Optional[S]
 266     subdirectory=None,  # type: Optional[S]
 267     extras=None,  # type: Optional[Iterable[S]]
 268 ):
 269     # type: (...) -> STRING_TYPE
 270     if extras is None:
 271         extras = []
 272     vcs_start = ""
 273     if vcs is not None:
 274         vcs_start = "{0}+".format(vcs)
 275         if not uri.startswith(vcs_start):
 276             uri = "{0}{1}".format(vcs_start, uri)
 277     if ref:
 278         uri = "{0}@{1}".format(uri, ref)
 279     if name:
 280         uri = "{0}#egg={1}".format(uri, name)
 281         if extras:
 282             extras_string = extras_to_string(extras)
 283             uri = "{0}{1}".format(uri, extras_string)
 284     if subdirectory:
 285         uri = "{0}&subdirectory={1}".format(uri, subdirectory)
 286     return uri

 289 def _get_parsed_url(url):
 290     # type: (S) -> Url
 291     """
 292     This is a stand-in function for `urllib3.util.parse_url`
 293 
 294     The orignal function doesn't handle special characters very well, this simply splits
 295     out the authentication section, creates the parsed url, then puts the authentication
 296     section back in, bypassing validation.
 297 
 298     :return: The new, parsed URL object
 299     :rtype: :class:`~urllib3.util.url.Url`
 300     """
 301 
 302     try:
 303         parsed = urllib3_parse(url)
 304     except ValueError:
 305         scheme, _, url = url.partition("://")
 306         auth, _, url = url.rpartition("@")
 307         url = "{scheme}://{url}".format(scheme=scheme, url=url)
 308         parsed = urllib3_parse(url)._replace(auth=auth)
 309     return parsed

 312 def convert_direct_url_to_url(direct_url):
 313     # type: (AnyStr) -> AnyStr
 314     """Converts direct URLs to standard, link-style URLs
 315 
 316     Given a direct url as defined by *PEP 508*, convert to a :class:`~pip_shims.shims.Link`
 317     compatible URL by moving the name and extras into an **egg_fragment**.
 318 
 319     :param str direct_url: A pep-508 compliant direct url.
 320     :return: A reformatted URL for use with Link objects and :class:`~pip_shims.shims.InstallRequirement` objects.
 321     :rtype: AnyStr
 322     """
 323     direct_match = DIRECT_URL_RE.match(direct_url)  # type: Optional[Match]
 324     if direct_match is None:
 325         url_match = URL_RE.match(direct_url)
 326         if url_match or is_valid_url(direct_url):
 327             return direct_url
 328     match_dict = (
 329         {}
 330     )  # type: Dict[STRING_TYPE, Union[Tuple[STRING_TYPE, ...], STRING_TYPE]]
 331     if direct_match is not None:
 332         match_dict = direct_match.groupdict()  # type: ignore
 333     if not match_dict:
 334         raise ValueError(
 335             "Failed converting value to normal URL, is it a direct URL? {0!r}".format(
 336                 direct_url
 337             )
 338         )
 339     url_segments = [match_dict.get(s) for s in ("scheme", "host", "path", "pathsep")]
 340     url = ""  # type: STRING_TYPE
 341     url = "".join([s for s in url_segments if s is not None])  # type: ignore
 342     new_url = build_vcs_uri(
 343         None,
 344         url,
 345         ref=match_dict.get("ref"),
 346         name=match_dict.get("name"),
 347         extras=match_dict.get("extras"),
 348         subdirectory=match_dict.get("subdirectory"),
 349     )
 350     return new_url
 351

 353 def convert_url_to_direct_url(url, name=None):
 354     # type: (AnyStr, Optional[AnyStr]) -> AnyStr
 355     """
 356     Converts normal link-style URLs to direct urls.
 357 
 358     Given a :class:`~pip_shims.shims.Link` compatible URL, convert to a direct url as
 359     defined by *PEP 508* by extracting the name and extras from the **egg_fragment**.
 360 
 361     :param AnyStr url: A :class:`~pip_shims.shims.InstallRequirement` compliant URL.
 362     :param Optiona[AnyStr] name: A name to use in case the supplied URL doesn't provide one.
 363     :return: A pep-508 compliant direct url.
 364     :rtype: AnyStr
 365 
 366     :raises ValueError: Raised when the URL can't be parsed or a name can't be found.
 367     :raises TypeError: When a non-string input is provided.
 368     """
 369     if not isinstance(url, six.string_types):
 370         raise TypeError(
 371             "Expected a string to convert to a direct url, got {0!r}".format(url)
 372         )
 373     direct_match = DIRECT_URL_RE.match(url)
 374     if direct_match:
 375         return url
 376     url_match = URL_RE.match(url)
 377     if url_match is None or not url_match.groupdict():
 378         raise ValueError("Failed parse a valid URL from {0!r}".format(url))
 379     match_dict = url_match.groupdict()
 380     url_segments = [match_dict.get(s) for s in ("scheme", "host", "path", "pathsep")]
 381     name = match_dict.get("name", name)
 382     extras = match_dict.get("extras")
 383     new_url = ""
 384     if extras and not name:
 385         url_segments.append(extras)
 386     elif extras and name:
 387         new_url = "{0}{1}@ ".format(name, extras)
 388     else:
 389         if name is not None:
 390             new_url = "{0}@ ".format(name)
 391         else:
 392             raise ValueError(
 393                 "Failed to construct direct url: "
 394                 "No name could be parsed from {0!r}".format(url)
 395             )
 396     if match_dict.get("ref"):
 397         url_segments.append("@{0}".format(match_dict.get("ref")))
 398     url = "".join([s for s in url if s is not None])
 399     url = "{0}{1}".format(new_url, url)
 400     return url

 403 def get_version(pipfile_entry):
 404     # type: (Union[STRING_TYPE, Dict[STRING_TYPE, Union[STRING_TYPE, bool, Iterable[STRING_TYPE]]]]) -> STRING_TYPE
 405     if str(pipfile_entry) == "{}" or is_star(pipfile_entry):
 406         return ""
 407 
 408     if hasattr(pipfile_entry, "keys") and "version" in pipfile_entry:
 409         if is_star(pipfile_entry.get("version")):
 410             return ""
 411         return pipfile_entry.get("version", "").strip().lstrip("(").rstrip(")")
 412 
 413     if isinstance(pipfile_entry, six.string_types):
 414         return pipfile_entry.strip().lstrip("(").rstrip(")")
 415     return ""

 418 def strip_extras_markers_from_requirement(req):
 419     # type: (TRequirement) -> TRequirement
 420     """
 421     Strips extras markers from requirement instances.
 422 
 423     Given a :class:`~packaging.requirements.Requirement` instance with markers defining
 424     *extra == 'name'*, strip out the extras from the markers and return the cleaned
 425     requirement
 426 
 427     :param PackagingRequirement req: A packaging requirement to clean
 428     :return: A cleaned requirement
 429     :rtype: PackagingRequirement
 430     """
 431     if req is None:
 432         raise TypeError("Must pass in a valid requirement, received {0!r}".format(req))
 433     if getattr(req, "marker", None) is not None:
 434         marker = req.marker  # type: TMarker
 435         marker._markers = _strip_extras_markers(marker._markers)
 436         if not marker._markers:
 437             req.marker = None
 438         else:
 439             req.marker = marker
 440     return req
 441 
 442 
 443 def _strip_extras_markers(marker):
 444     # type: (Union[MarkerTuple, List[Union[MarkerTuple, str]]]) -> List[Union[MarkerTuple, str]]
 445     if marker is None or not isinstance(marker, (list, tuple)):
 446         raise TypeError("Expecting a marker type, received {0!r}".format(marker))
 447     markers_to_remove = []
 448     # iterate forwards and generate a list of indexes to remove first, then reverse the
 449     # list so we can remove the text that normally occurs after (but we will already
 450     # be past it in the loop)
 451     for i, marker_list in enumerate(marker):
 452         if isinstance(marker_list, list):
 453             cleaned = _strip_extras_markers(marker_list)
 454             if not cleaned:
 455                 markers_to_remove.append(i)
 456         elif isinstance(marker_list, tuple) and marker_list[0].value == "extra":
 457             markers_to_remove.append(i)
 458     for i in reversed(markers_to_remove):
 459         del marker[i]
 460         if i > 0 and marker[i - 1] == "and":
 461             del marker[i - 1]
 462     return marker

 476 def get_default_pyproject_backend():
 477     # type: () -> STRING_TYPE
 478     st_version = get_setuptools_version()
 479     if st_version is not None:
 480         parsed_st_version = parse_version(st_version)
 481         if parsed_st_version >= parse_version("40.8.0"):
 482             return "setuptools.build_meta:__legacy__"
 483     return "setuptools.build_meta"

 486 def get_pyproject(path):
 487     # type: (Union[STRING_TYPE, Path]) -> Optional[Tuple[List[STRING_TYPE], STRING_TYPE]]
 488     """
 489     Given a base path, look for the corresponding ``pyproject.toml`` file and return its
 490     build_requires and build_backend.
 491 
 492     :param AnyStr path: The root path of the project, should be a directory (will be truncated)
 493     :return: A 2 tuple of build requirements and the build backend
 494     :rtype: Optional[Tuple[List[AnyStr], AnyStr]]
 495     """
 496     if not path:
 497         return
 498     from vistir.compat import Path
 499 
 500     if not isinstance(path, Path):
 501         path = Path(path)
 502     if not path.is_dir():
 503         path = path.parent
 504     pp_toml = path.joinpath("pyproject.toml")
 505     setup_py = path.joinpath("setup.py")
 506     if not pp_toml.exists():
 507         if not setup_py.exists():
 508             return None
 509         requires = ["setuptools>=40.8", "wheel"]
 510         backend = get_default_pyproject_backend()
 511     else:
 512         pyproject_data = {}
 513         with io.open(pp_toml.as_posix(), encoding="utf-8") as fh:
 514             pyproject_data = tomlkit.loads(fh.read())
 515         build_system = pyproject_data.get("build-system", None)
 516         if build_system is None:
 517             if setup_py.exists():
 518                 requires = ["setuptools>=40.8", "wheel"]
 519                 backend = get_default_pyproject_backend()
 520             else:
 521                 requires = ["setuptools>=40.8", "wheel"]
 522                 backend = get_default_pyproject_backend()
 523             build_system = {"requires": requires, "build-backend": backend}
 524             pyproject_data["build_system"] = build_system
 525         else:
 526             requires = build_system.get("requires", ["setuptools>=40.8", "wheel"])
 527             backend = build_system.get("build-backend", get_default_pyproject_backend())
 528     return requires, backend

 531 def split_markers_from_line(line):
 532     # type: (AnyStr) -> Tuple[AnyStr, Optional[AnyStr]]
 533     """Split markers from a dependency"""
 534     quote_chars = ["'", '"']
 535     line_quote = next(
 536         iter(quote for quote in quote_chars if line.startswith(quote)), None
 537     )
 538     if line_quote and line.endswith(line_quote):
 539         line = line.strip(line_quote)
 540     if not any(line.startswith(uri_prefix) for uri_prefix in SCHEME_LIST):
 541         marker_sep = ";"
 542     else:
 543         marker_sep = "; "
 544     markers = None
 545     if marker_sep in line:
 546         line, markers = line.split(marker_sep, 1)
 547         markers = markers.strip() if markers else None
 548     return line, markers
 549 
 550 
 551 def split_vcs_method_from_uri(uri):
 552     # type: (AnyStr) -> Tuple[Optional[STRING_TYPE], STRING_TYPE]
 553     """Split a vcs+uri formatted uri into (vcs, uri)"""
 554     vcs_start = "{0}+"
 555     vcs = next(
 556         iter([vcs for vcs in VCS_LIST if uri.startswith(vcs_start.format(vcs))]), None
 557     )
 558     if vcs:
 559         vcs, uri = uri.split("+", 1)
 560     return vcs, uri
 561 
 562 
 563 def split_ref_from_uri(uri):
 564     # type: (AnyStr) -> Tuple[AnyStr, Optional[AnyStr]]
 565     """
 566     Given a path or URI, check for a ref and split it from the path if it is present,
 567     returning a tuple of the original input and the ref or None.
 568 
 569     :param AnyStr uri: The path or URI to split
 570     :returns: A 2-tuple of the path or URI and the ref
 571     :rtype: Tuple[AnyStr, Optional[AnyStr]]
 572     """
 573     if not isinstance(uri, six.string_types):
 574         raise TypeError("Expected a string, received {0!r}".format(uri))
 575     parsed = _get_parsed_url(uri)
 576     path = parsed.path if parsed.path else ""
 577     scheme = parsed.scheme if parsed.scheme else ""
 578     ref = None
 579     if scheme != "file" and "@" in path:
 580         path, _, ref = path.rpartition("@")
 581     parsed = parsed._replace(path=path)
 582     return (parsed.url, ref)

 611 def key_from_ireq(ireq):
 612     """Get a standardized key for an InstallRequirement."""
 613     if ireq.req is None and ireq.link is not None:
 614         return str(ireq.link)
 615     else:
 616         return key_from_req(ireq.req)

 619 def key_from_req(req):
 620     """Get an all-lowercase version of the requirement's name."""
 621     if hasattr(req, "key"):
 622         # from pkg_resources, such as installed dists for pip-sync
 623         key = req.key
 624     else:
 625         # from packaging, such as install requirements from requirements.txt
 626         key = req.name
 627 
 628     key = key.replace("_", "-").lower()
 629     return key
 630 
 631 
 632 def _requirement_to_str_lowercase_name(requirement):
 633     """Formats a packaging.requirements.Requirement with a lowercase name.
 634 
 635     This is simply a copy of
 636     https://github.com/pypa/packaging/blob/16.8/packaging/requirements.py#L109-L124
 637     modified to lowercase the dependency name.
 638 
 639     Previously, we were invoking the original Requirement.__str__ method and
 640     lower-casing the entire result, which would lowercase the name, *and* other,
 641     important stuff that should not be lower-cased (such as the marker). See
 642     this issue for more information: https://github.com/pypa/pipenv/issues/2113.
 643     """
 644     parts = [requirement.name.lower()]
 645 
 646     if requirement.extras:
 647         parts.append("[{0}]".format(",".join(sorted(requirement.extras))))
 648 
 649     if requirement.specifier:
 650         parts.append(str(requirement.specifier))
 651 
 652     if requirement.url:
 653         parts.append("@ {0}".format(requirement.url))
 654 
 655     if requirement.marker:
 656         parts.append("; {0}".format(requirement.marker))
 657 
 658     return "".join(parts)
 659 
 660 
 661 def format_requirement(ireq):
 662     """Formats an `InstallRequirement` instance as a string.
 663 
 664     Generic formatter for pretty printing InstallRequirements to the terminal
 665     in a less verbose way than using its `__str__` method.
 666 
 667     :param :class:`InstallRequirement` ireq: A pip **InstallRequirement** instance.
 668     :return: A formatted string for prettyprinting
 669     :rtype: str
 670     """
 671     if ireq.editable:
 672         line = "-e {}".format(ireq.link)
 673     else:
 674         line = _requirement_to_str_lowercase_name(ireq.req)
 675 
 676     if str(ireq.req.marker) != str(ireq.markers):
 677         if not ireq.req.marker:
 678             line = "{}; {}".format(line, ireq.markers)
 679         else:
 680             name, markers = line.split(";", 1)
 681             markers = markers.strip()
 682             line = "{}; ({}) and ({})".format(name, markers, ireq.markers)
 683 
 684     return line
 685

 687 def format_specifier(ireq):
 688     """Generic formatter for pretty printing specifiers.
 689 
 690     Pretty-prints specifiers from InstallRequirements for output to terminal.
 691 
 692     :param :class:`InstallRequirement` ireq: A pip **InstallRequirement** instance.
 693     :return: A string of specifiers in the given install requirement or <any>
 694     :rtype: str
 695     """
 696     # TODO: Ideally, this is carried over to the pip library itself
 697     specs = ireq.specifier._specs if ireq.req is not None else []
 698     specs = sorted(specs, key=lambda x: x._spec[1])
 699     return ",".join(str(s) for s in specs) or "<any>"

 701 
 702 def get_pinned_version(ireq):
 703     """Get the pinned version of an InstallRequirement.
 704 
 705     An InstallRequirement is considered pinned if:
 706 
 707     - Is not editable
 708     - It has exactly one specifier
 709     - That specifier is "=="
 710     - The version does not contain a wildcard
 711 
 712     Examples:
 713         django==1.8   # pinned
 714         django>1.8    # NOT pinned
 715         django~=1.8   # NOT pinned
 716         django==1.*   # NOT pinned
 717 
 718     Raises `TypeError` if the input is not a valid InstallRequirement, or
 719     `ValueError` if the InstallRequirement is not pinned.
 720     """
 721     try:
 722         specifier = ireq.specifier
 723     except AttributeError:
 724         raise TypeError("Expected InstallRequirement, not {}".format(type(ireq).__name__))
 725 
 726     if getattr(ireq, "editable", False):
 727         raise ValueError("InstallRequirement is editable")
 728     if not specifier:
 729         raise ValueError("InstallRequirement has no version specification")
 730     if len(specifier._specs) != 1:
 731         raise ValueError("InstallRequirement has multiple specifications")
 732 
 733     op, version = next(iter(specifier._specs))._spec
 734     if op not in ("==", "===") or version.endswith(".*"):
 735         raise ValueError("InstallRequirement not pinned (is {0!r})".format(op + version))
 736 
 737     return version
 738 
 739 
 740 def is_pinned_requirement(ireq):
 741     """
 742     Returns whether an InstallRequirement is a "pinned" requirement.
 743 
 744     An InstallRequirement is considered pinned if:
 745 
 746     - Is not editable
 747     - It has exactly one specifier
 748     - That specifier is "=="
 749     - The version does not contain a wildcard
 750 
 751     Examples:
 752         django==1.8   # pinned
 753         django>1.8    # NOT pinned
 754         django~=1.8   # NOT pinned
 755         django==1.*   # NOT pinned
 756     """
 757 
 758     try:
 759         get_pinned_version(ireq)
 760     except (TypeError, ValueError):
 761         return False
 762     return True
 763 
 764 
 765 def as_tuple(ireq):
 766     """
 767     Pulls out the (name: str, version:str, extras:(str)) tuple from the pinned InstallRequirement.
 768     """
 769 
 770     if not is_pinned_requirement(ireq):
 771         raise TypeError("Expected a pinned InstallRequirement, got {}".format(ireq))
 772 
 773     name = key_from_req(ireq.req)
 774     version = next(iter(ireq.specifier._specs))._spec[1]
 775     extras = tuple(sorted(ireq.extras))
 776     return name, version, extras

 779 def full_groupby(iterable, key=None):
 780     """
 781     Like groupby(), but sorts the input on the group key first.
 782     """
 783 
 784     return groupby(sorted(iterable, key=key), key=key)

 789     Map a function over a collection and flatten the result by one-level

 792     return chain.from_iterable(map(fn, collection))

 795 def lookup_table(values, key=None, keyval=None, unique=False, use_lists=False):
 796     """
 797     Builds a dict-based lookup table (index) elegantly.
 798 
 799     Supports building normal and unique lookup tables.  For example:
 800 
 801     >>> assert lookup_table(
 802     ...     ['foo', 'bar', 'baz', 'qux', 'quux'], lambda s: s[0]) == {
 803     ...     'b': {'bar', 'baz'},
 804     ...     'f': {'foo'},
 805     ...     'q': {'quux', 'qux'}
 806     ... }
 807 
 808     For key functions that uniquely identify values, set unique=True:
 809 
 810     >>> assert lookup_table(
 811     ...     ['foo', 'bar', 'baz', 'qux', 'quux'], lambda s: s[0], unique=True) == {
 812     ...     'b': 'baz',
 813     ...     'f': 'foo',
 814     ...     'q': 'quux'
 815     ... }
 816 
 817     The values of the resulting lookup table will be values, not sets.
 818 
 819     For extra power, you can even change the values while building up the LUT.
 820     To do so, use the `keyval` function instead of the `key` arg:
 821 
 822     >>> assert lookup_table(
 823     ...     ['foo', 'bar', 'baz', 'qux', 'quux'],
 824     ...     keyval=lambda s: (s[0], s[1:])) == {
 825     ...     'b': {'ar', 'az'},
 826     ...     'f': {'oo'},
 827     ...     'q': {'uux', 'ux'}
 828     ... }
 829     """
 830 
 831     if keyval is None:
 832         if key is None:
 833             keyval = lambda v: v
 834         else:
 835             keyval = lambda v: (key(v), v)
 836 
 837     if unique:
 838         return dict(keyval(v) for v in values)
 839 
 840     lut = {}
 841     for value in values:
 842         k, v = keyval(value)
 843         try:
 844             s = lut[k]
 845         except KeyError:
 846             if use_lists:
 847                 s = lut[k] = list()
 848             else:
 849                 s = lut[k] = set()
 850         if use_lists:
 851             s.append(v)
 852         else:
 853             s.add(v)
 854     return dict(lut)
 855

 867 def make_install_requirement(
 868     name, version=None, extras=None, markers=None, constraint=False
 869 ):
 870     """
 871     Generates an :class:`~pip._internal.req.req_install.InstallRequirement`.
 872 
 873     Create an InstallRequirement from the supplied metadata.
 874 
 875     :param name: The requirement's name.
 876     :type name: str
 877     :param version: The requirement version (must be pinned).
 878     :type version: str.
 879     :param extras: The desired extras.
 880     :type extras: list[str]
 881     :param markers: The desired markers, without a preceding semicolon.
 882     :type markers: str
 883     :param constraint: Whether to flag the requirement as a constraint, defaults to False.
 884     :param constraint: bool, optional
 885     :return: A generated InstallRequirement
 886     :rtype: :class:`~pip._internal.req.req_install.InstallRequirement`
 887     """
 888 
 889     # If no extras are specified, the extras string is blank
 890     from pip_shims.shims import install_req_from_line
 891 
 892     extras_string = ""
 893     requirement_string = "{0}".format(name)
 894     if extras:
 895         # Sort extras for stability
 896         extras_string = "[{}]".format(",".join(sorted(extras)))
 897         requirement_string = "{0}{1}".format(requirement_string, extras_string)
 898     if version:
 899         requirement_string = "{0}=={1}".format(requirement_string, str(version))
 900     if markers:
 901         requirement_string = "{0}; {1}".format(requirement_string, str(markers))
 902     return install_req_from_line(requirement_string, constraint=constraint)
 903

 905 def version_from_ireq(ireq):

 909     :type ireq: :class:`~pip._internal.req.req_install.InstallRequirement`
 910     :return: The version of the InstallRequirement.
 911     :rtype: str
 912     """
 913 
 914     return next(iter(ireq.specifier._specs)).version

 917 def _get_requires_python(candidate):
 918     # type: (Any) -> str
 919     requires_python = getattr(candidate, "requires_python", None)
 920     if requires_python is not None:
 921         link = getattr(candidate, "location", getattr(candidate, "link", None))
 922         requires_python = getattr(link, "requires_python", None)
 923     return requires_python
 924 
 925 
 926 def clean_requires_python(candidates):
 927     """Get a cleaned list of all the candidates with valid specifiers in the `requires_python` attributes."""
 928     all_candidates = []
 929     sys_version = ".".join(map(str, sys.version_info[:3]))
 930     from packaging.version import parse as parse_version
 931 
 932     py_version = parse_version(os.environ.get("PIP_PYTHON_VERSION", sys_version))
 933     for c in candidates:
 934         requires_python = _get_requires_python(c)
 935         if requires_python:
 936             # Old specifications had people setting this to single digits
 937             # which is effectively the same as '>=digit,<digit+1'
 938             if requires_python.isdigit():
 939                 requires_python = ">={0},<{1}".format(
 940                     requires_python, int(requires_python) + 1
 941                 )
 942             try:
 943                 specifierset = SpecifierSet(requires_python)
 944             except InvalidSpecifier:
 945                 continue
 946             else:
 947                 if not specifierset.contains(py_version):
 948                     continue
 949         all_candidates.append(c)
 950     return all_candidates
 951 
 952 
 953 def fix_requires_python_marker(requires_python):
 954     from packaging.requirements import Requirement as PackagingRequirement
 955 
 956     marker_str = ""
 957     if any(requires_python.startswith(op) for op in Specifier._operators.keys()):
 958         spec_dict = defaultdict(set)
 959         # We are checking first if we have  leading specifier operator
 960         # if not, we can assume we should be doing a == comparison
 961         specifierset = list(SpecifierSet(requires_python))
 962         # for multiple specifiers, the correct way to represent that in
 963         # a specifierset is `Requirement('fakepkg; python_version<"3.0,>=2.6"')`
 964         marker_key = Variable("python_version")
 965         for spec in specifierset:
 966             operator, val = spec._spec
 967             cleaned_val = Value(val).serialize().replace('"', "")
 968             spec_dict[Op(operator).serialize()].add(cleaned_val)
 969         marker_str = " and ".join(
 970             [
 971                 "{0}{1}'{2}'".format(marker_key.serialize(), op, ",".join(vals))
 972                 for op, vals in spec_dict.items()
 973             ]
 974         )
 975     marker_to_add = PackagingRequirement("fakepkg; {0}".format(marker_str)).marker
 976     return marker_to_add

 979 def normalize_name(pkg):
 980     # type: (AnyStr) -> AnyStr
 981     """Given a package name, return its normalized, non-canonicalized form.
 982 
 983     :param AnyStr pkg: The name of a package
 984     :return: A normalized package name
 985     :rtype: AnyStr

 992 def get_name_variants(pkg):
 993     # type: (STRING_TYPE) -> Set[STRING_TYPE]
 994     """
 995     Given a packager name, get the variants of its name for both the canonicalized
 996     and "safe" forms.
 997 
 998     :param AnyStr pkg: The package to lookup
 999     :returns: A list of names.
1000     :rtype: Set
1001     """
1002 
1003     if not isinstance(pkg, six.string_types):
1004         raise TypeError("must provide a string to derive package names")
1005     from pkg_resources import safe_name
1006     from packaging.utils import canonicalize_name
1007 
1008     pkg = pkg.lower()
1009     names = {safe_name(pkg), canonicalize_name(pkg), pkg.replace("-", "_")}
1010     return names

1013 def read_source(path, encoding="utf-8"):
1014     # type: (S, S) -> S
1015     """
1016     Read a source file and get the contents with proper encoding for Python 2/3.
1017 
1018     :param AnyStr path: the file path
1019     :param AnyStr encoding: the encoding that defaults to UTF-8
1020     :returns: The contents of the source file
1021     :rtype: AnyStr
1022     """
1023     if six.PY3:
1024         with open(path, "r", encoding=encoding) as fp:
1025             return fp.read()
1026     else:
1027         with open(path, "r") as fp:
1028             return fp.read()
